		<blockquote>
		<h1 align="center"><span style="color:#05A0FB; font-size:48px; ">Non-invasive glucose monitoring using light reflection techniques.</span></h1>
		<p align="center"><span style="font-style:italic; color:#05A0FB;">Assessing if using light reflection is a feasible technique for non-invasive glucose monitoring for general diabetic patients. </span></p>
		
		<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Some researchers have proved that it's possible to read glucose levels using mid to high IR light. This is done by detecting how much IR light is being reflected - different levels of glucose within the blood will change how much of the IR light is absorbed/reflected.   </p>
		<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Yet many of these researchers haven't really considered consumers. All of the research found so far shows that all of these non-invasive glucose monitoring devices are large (some larger then my 17" laptop!) and very expensive (some of the parts cost a few thousand by themselves). These are some of the main reasons why, at it's current state, this is not a feasible technology for consumers - both individual users and hospitals or care centers. For this thesis I will attempt to design a model for this that does keep the two points above in mind, while hopefully achieving the goal of non-invasively reading blood glucose.</p>
		<p align="center"> I will expand this page more, however I am currently at the research stage of my thesis and haven't begun experimenting yet. </p>

